                      Part I

                      Ex 2.1

                      Prove Theorem 2.2.

                      Proof

                      Theorem 2.2: (a,b)=(c,d) if and only if a=c and b=d. To prove it, one direction is obvious. Now suppose (a,b)=(c,d), by Definition 2.1, we have

                      {{a},{a,b}}={{c},{c,d}}

                      from the definition of set equality, this means {a}∈{{c},{c,d}}, which gives {a}={c}, which means a=c, similarly we can have {a,b}={c,d}, or {a,b}={a,d}, which means b∈{a,d}, thus b=d.

                      Ex 2.2

                      Let S be a relation and let D(S) be its domain. The relation S is said to be

                      • i) reflexive if a∈D(S) implies (a,a)∈S,

                      • ii) symmetric if (a,b)∈S implies (b,a)∈S,

                      • iii) transitive if (a,b)∈S and (b,c)∈S implies (a,c)∈S.

                      A relation which is symmetric, reflexive and transitive is called an equivalence relation. Determine which of these properties is possessed by S, if S is the set of all pairs of real numbers (x,y) such that a) x≤y, b) x<y, c) x<|y|, d) x2+y2=1, e) x2+y2<0, f) x2+x=y2+y.

                      Solution

                      a) reflexive is true since x≤x for any x, symmetric is false since (x,x+1)∈S but (x+1,x) is not, transitive is true. b) reflexive is false, symmetric is false, transitive is true. c) reflexive is false, symmetric is false, transitive is false since (1,−2)∈S and (−2,0)∈S but (1,0) is not. d) reflexive is false since (0,0)∉S, symmetric is true, transitive is false. e) since D(S)=S=∅, reflexive, symmetric and transitive are all true. f) reflexive is true, symmetric is true, transitive is true.

                      Ex 2.3

                      The following functions F and G are defined for all real x by the equations given. In each case where the composite function G∘F can be formed, give the domain of G∘F and a formula (or fomulas) for (G∘F)(x). a) F(x)=1−x,G(x)=x2+2x, b) F(x)=x+5,G(x)=|x|/x,if x≠0,G(0)=1. c) F(x)={2x,if 0≤x≤1,1,otherwise,G(x)={x2,if 0≤x≤1,1,otherwise Find F(x) if G(x) and G[F(x)] are given as follows: d) G(x)=x3,G[F(x)]=x3−3x2+3x−1. e) G(x)=3+x+x2,G[F(x)]=x2−3x+5.

                      Solution

                      a) D(G∘F)=R,(G∘F)(x)=G(1−x)=x2−4x+3. b) D(G∘F)=R,(G∘F)(x)=|x+5|/(x+5)if x≠−5,G(−5)=0. c) D(G∘F)=R and

                      (G∘F)(x)={4x2,if 0≤x≤1/2,1,otherwise

                      d) G[F(x)]=(x−1)3, thus F(x)=x−1, e) G[F(x)]=3+(1−x)+(1−x)2, thus F(x)=1−x.

                      Ex 2.4

                      Given three functions F,G,H, what restrictions must be placed on their domains so that the following four composite functions can be defined?

                      G∘F,H∘G,H∘(G∘F),(H∘G)∘F.

                      Assuming that H∘(G∘F) and (H∘G)∘F can be defined, prove the associative law:

                      H∘(G∘F)=(H∘G)∘F

                      Solution

                      For G∘F, we must restrict R(F)⊂D(G). For H∘G, we must restrict R(G)⊂D(H). For H∘(G∘F) and (H∘G)∘F, we must restrict both R(F)⊂D(G) and R(G)⊂D(H). Assume H∘(G∘F) and (H∘G)∘F can be defined, then

                      D(H∘(G∘F))=D((H∘G)∘F)=D(F)

                      For any x∈D(F), we have

                      (H∘(G∘F))(x)=((H∘G)∘F)(x)=H(G(F(x)))

                      by Theorem 2.6, the two functions H∘(G∘F) and (H∘G)∘F are equal.

                      Ex 2.5

                      Prove the following set-theoretic identities for union and intersection: a) A∪(B∪C)=(A∪B)∪C,A∩(B∩C)=(A∩B)∩C. b) A∩(B∪C)=(A∩B)∪(A∩C). c) (A∪B)∩(A∪C)=A∪(B∩C). d) (A∪B)∩(B∪C)∩(C∪A)=(A∩B)∪(A∩C)∪(B∩C). e) A∩(B−C)=(A∩B)−(A∩C). f) (A−C)∩(B−C)=(A∩B)−C. g) (A−B)∪B=A if and only if B⊆A.

                      Proof

                      a) It is easy to see that

                      A∪(B∪C)=(A∪B)∪C=A∪B∪CA∩(B∩C)=(A∩B)∩C=A∩B∩C

                      b) If x∈A∩(B∪C), then x∈A, and either x∈B or x∈C, thus either x∈A∩B or x∈A∩C, which means x∈(A∩B)∪(A∩C), the converse is also true. c) If x∈(A∪B)∩(A∪C), then both x∈A∪B and x∈A∪C, if x∈A, then x∈A∪(B∩C), if x∉A, then from x∈A∪B we have x∈B, from x∈A∪C we have x∈C, thus x∈B∩C, and x∈A∪(B∩C). On the other hand, if x∈A∪(B∩C), then either x∈A, which means x∈(A∪B)∩(A∪C), or x∈B∩C, thus x∈A∪B and x∈A∪C, which means x∈(A∪B)∩(A∪C). d) It is easy to see that x must lies in at least two of the three sets A,B,C. e) We have

                      x∈A∩(B−C)⇔(x∈A)∧(x∈B)∧(x∉C)⇔(x∈A∩B)∧(x∉A∩C)⇔x∈(A∩B)−(A∩C)

                      f) We have

                      x∈(A−C)∩(B−C)⇔(x∈A)∧(x∈B)∧(x∉C)⇔(x∈A∩B)∧(x∉C)⇔x∈(A∩B)−C

                      g) If (A−B)∪B=A, then ∀x∈B, we have x∈(A−B)∪B, thus x∈A, which means B⊆A. Conversely, if B⊆A, then (A−B)∪B⊆A, and ∀a∈A, we have either a∈B, or a∉B, the latter means a∈A−B, thus a∈(A−B)∪B, this shows (A−B)∪B=A.

                      Ex 2.6

                      Let f:S→T be a function. If A and B are arbitrary subsets of S, prove that

                      f(A∪B)=f(A)∪f(B),f(A∩B)⊆f(A)∩f(B)

                      Generalize to arbitrary unions and intersections.

                      Proof

                      First let y∈f(A∪B), then ∃x∈A∪B such that f(x)=y. Since x∈A or x∈B, we have f(x)∈f(A)∪f(B), so f(A∪B)⊆f(A)∪f(B). On the other hand, for any y∈f(A)∪f(B), we have y∈f(A) or y∈f(B), then y=f(a) for some a∈A or y=f(b) for some b∈B, in either case, there is x∈A∪B such that y=f(x), so y∈A∪B and f(A)∪f(B)⊆f(A∪B). Next, let y∈f(A∩B), then ∃x∈A∩B such that f(x)=y, this means y∈f(A) and y∈f(B). Conversely let A={1,2},B={1,3} and f is defined with f(1)=1,f(2)=f(3)=0, then f(A∩B)={1}, but f(A)∩f(B)={0,1}. Generalize to arbitrary unions and intersections, we have

                      f(∪iAi)=⋃if(Ai),f(∩iAi)=⋂if(Ai)

                      the proof is similar with the proof when i=2 and is ommited.

                      Ex 2.7

                      Let f:S→T be a function. If Y⊆T, we denote by f−1(Y) the largest subset of S which f maps into Y. That is

                      f−1(Y)={x:x∈S,f(x)∈Y}.

                      The set f−1(Y) is called the inverse image of Y under f. Prove the following for arbitrary subsets X of S and Y of T. a) X⊆f−1[f(X)], b) f[f−1(Y)]⊆Y, c) f−1[Y1∪Y2]=f−1(Y1)∪f−1(Y2), d) f−1(Y1∩Y2)=f−1(Y1)∩f−1(Y2), e) f−1(T−Y)=S−f−1(Y). f) Generalize (c) and (d) to arbitrary unions and intersections.

                      Proof

                      a) Let x∈X⊆S, then f(x)∈f(X), by definition, x∈f−1[f(X)]. b) For ∀y∈f[f−1(Y)],∃x∈f−1(Y), s.t. y=f(x), but if x∈f−1(Y), then f(x)∈Y by definition, thus y∈Y. c) We have

                      x∈f−1(Y1∪Y2)⇔f(x)∈(Y1∪Y2)⇔(f(x)∈Y1)∨(f(x)∈Y2)⇔(x∈f−1(Y1))∨(x∈f−1(Y2))⇔x∈f−1(Y1)∪f−1(Y2)

                      d) We have

                      x∈f−1(Y1∩Y2)⇔f(x)∈(Y1∩Y2)⇔(f(x)∈Y1)∧(f(x)∈Y2)⇔(x∈f−1(Y1))∧(x∈f−1(Y2))⇔x∈f−1(Y1)∩f−1(Y2)

                      e) We have

                      x∈f−1(T−Y)⇔(x∈S)∧(f(x)∈T−Y)⇔(x∈S)∧(f(x)∉Y)⇔(x∈S)∧(x∉f−1(Y))⇔x∈S−f−1(Y)

                      f) We can have f−1(∪iYi)=⋃if−1(Yi) and f−1(∩iYi)=⋂if−1(Yi).

                      Ex 2.8

                      Refer to Exercise 2.7. Prove that f[f−1(Y)]=Y for every subset Y of T if and only if T=f(S).

                      Proof

                      We already have f[f−1(Y)]⊆Y, thus we only have to prove f[f−1(Y)]⊇Y if and only if T=f(S). First suppose T=F(S), for ∀y∈Y, we have y∈T, thus y∈f(S), which means ∃x∈S such that f(x)=y, this shows x∈f−1(Y) by definition of f−1(Y), thus y∈f[f−1(Y)]. Next suppose f[f−1(Y)]⊇Y for every subset Y of T, then since T is a subset of T, we have T⊆f[f−1(T)]⊆f(S), since it is obvious that f(S)⊆T, we can finish the proof.

                      Ex 2.9

                      Let f:S→T be a function. Prove that the following statements are equivalent. a) f is one-to-one on S. b) f(A∩B)=f(A)∩f(B) for all subsets A,B of S. c) f−1[f(A)]=A for every subset A of S. d) For all disjoint subsets A and B of S, the images f(A) and f(B) are disjoint. e) For all subsets A and B of S with B⊆A, we have

                      f(A−B)=f(A)−f(B).

                      Proof

                      (a) implies (b): For y=f(x)∈f(A∩B), we have x∈A∩B and (f(x)∈f(A))∧(f(x)∈f(B)), this means f(A∩B)⊆f(A)∩f(B), now assume there is y′∈f(A)∩f(B), but y′∉f(A∩B), then ∃x′∈A−B and x″∈B−A such that f(x′)=f(x″)=y′, since A−B∩B−A=∅, we must have x′≠x″, this contradicts f being one-to-one on S. (b) implies (c): If x∈A, then f(x)∈f(A), thus x∈f−1[f(A)], which means A⊆f−1[f(A)]. Assume ∃a∈f−1[f(A)],a∉A, then f(a)∈f(A), from (b) we can also get f(A∩{a})=f(A)∩f({a})=f(a), but A∩{a}=∅, this means f(∅)=f(a), a contradiction. Thus we get f−1[f(A)]⊆A. (c) implies (d): Suppose A∩B=∅, and assume f(A)∩f(B)≠∅, then ∃c∈f(A)∩f(B), which means ∃a∈A,b∈B such that f(a)=f(b)=c, this means f−1[f({a})]=f−1({c})={a,b}. Using (c) we have f−1[f({a})]={a}. Since A∩B=∅, we must have a≠b and {a,b}≠{a}, this is a contradiction. (d) implies (e): The sets A−B and B are disjoint, thus f(A−B)∩f(B)=∅ by (d). Also if y∈f(A−B), then ∃x∈A−B⊆A such that y=f(x), thus y∈f(A) and f(A−B)⊆f(A). Now we proved f(A−B)⊆f(A)−f(B). To prove the converse, if y∈f(A)−f(B), then y∈f(A) and y∉f(B), thus ∃x∈A such that f(x)=y, moreover we must have x∉B otherwise y∈f(B), this means x∈A−B and y∈f(A−B).
                      (e) implies (a): Assume f is not one-to-one on S, then ∃a,b∈S with a≠b and f(a)=f(b):=c. Let A={a,b} and B={b}, then A−B={a}, using (e) we have f(A−B)=f({a})={c}=f(A)−f(B), but f(A)=f(B)={c} and thus f(A)−f(B)=∅, a contradiction.
